{"schema_version": "1.0", "timestamp": "2026-06-17T06:35:25.302810+00:00", "run_id": "20260617-163159-040724", "turn_id": "20260617-163244-960546", "event_id": "20260617-163159-040724-00008", "event": "assistant", "component": "integration", "phase": "output", "status": "completed", "source": "live", "message": "Assistant analysis result recorded", "duration_ms": null, "metrics": {}, "artifacts": [], "error": null, "payload": {"kind": "analysis_result", "content": {"input_type": "pdf", "input_ref": "[redacted-upload]", "metadata": {"title": "SIGA: Self-Evolving Coding-Agent Adapters for Scientific Simulation", "authors": ["Scientific Simulation"], "paper_id": "tmpmsmy3gdr_0d0bb1dafc"}, "summary": "# Scope  \nAddresses the challenge of translating scientific goals into executable configurations for advanced simulators, focusing on reducing setup time for domain scientists using tools like GEOS, OpenFOAM, and LAMMPS.\n\n# Core Contribution  \nIntroduces **SIGA** (Simulator-Interface Grounding Adapter), a self-evolving framework that bridges coding agents and scientific simulators by providing vocabulary, structural constraints, validation rules, and termination conditions via retrieval, procedural memory, and in-trajectory validation.\n\n# Method  \nLacks explicit details (structural check: \"missing_or_weak_method\"). Relies on pre-existing coding agents (e.g., Claude Code) and adapts them with grounding mechanisms, self-evolution via prior trajectories, and interface-specific validation/memory strategies.\n\n# Results  \n- SIGA achieves **TreeSim > 0.90** on GEOS in ~5 minutes, outperforming human experts by ~36\u00d7 speedup.  \n- Reduces across-seed variance by 16\u00d7 and improves held-out performance by 10%.  \n- Transfers to OpenFOAM/LAMMPS show interface-specific dominance of validation/memory mechanisms.  \n- Self-evolution enhances adapter performance, matching/halving hand-designed configurations.\n\n# Limitations  \nNo explicit limitations section detected. Structural checks indicate weak method description and lack of dedicated limitations analysis.", "key_findings": ["Core contribution: Introduces **SIGA** (Simulator-Interface Grounding Adapter), a self-evolving framework that bridges coding agents and scientific simulators by providing vocabulary, structural constraints, validation rules, and termination conditions via retrieval, procedural memory, and in-trajectory validation.", "SIGA achieves **TreeSim > 0.90** on GEOS in ~5 minutes, outperforming human experts by ~36\u00d7 speedup.", "Reduces across-seed variance by 16\u00d7 and improves held-out performance by 10%.", "Transfers to OpenFOAM/LAMMPS show interface-specific dominance of validation/memory mechanisms.", "Self-evolution enhances adapter performance, matching/halving hand-designed configurations."], "research_gaps": ["Limitations: No explicit limitations section detected. Structural checks indicate weak method description and lack of dedicated limitations analysis."], "recommended_papers": [], "apa_citations": [], "evidence": [], "peer_review": null, "paper_analysis": {"keyphrases": [{"text": "agents scientific simulators", "score": 0.6829, "section": "related_work", "source": "keybert_minilm"}, {"text": "agents scientific code", "score": 0.6345, "section": "related_work", "source": "keybert_minilm"}, {"text": "curated benchmarks scienceagentbench", "score": 0.6331, "section": "related_work", "source": "keybert_minilm"}, {"text": "scientific coding agents", "score": 0.6312, "section": "related_work", "source": "keybert_minilm"}, {"text": "benchmarks scienceagentbench", "score": 0.6232, "section": "related_work", "source": "keybert_minilm"}, {"text": "imposed scientific simulator", "score": 0.6173, "section": "introduction", "source": "keybert_minilm"}, {"text": "scientific simulation", "score": 0.6168, "section": "introduction", "source": "keybert_minilm"}, {"text": "scientific simulation central", "score": 0.6141, "section": "introduction", "source"